  "prompt": "What is infant mortality rate?",
  "response": "The infant mortality rate (IMR) is a measure used to assess the health of a population. It represents the number of deaths of infants under one year of age per 1,000 live births in a given year. The IMR is an important indicator of the overall health care system, maternal health, and the socio-economic conditions of a region, as it reflects factors such as access to medical care, nutrition, and sanitation.\n\nA lower IMR suggests better health conditions and services, while a higher IMR indicates potential issues in health care and living conditions. IMR can vary significantly between different countries and regions, influenced by various factors including economic status, healthcare availability, and public health policies.",
